# Rust Iterators

Iterators are Rust's composable, zero-cost loop abstraction. Use them instead of manual index loops.

## Core principle

An iterator chain is not slower than a `for` loop — the compiler fuses adapters into a single pass. Prefer chains for readability and to give LLVM more optimisation surface.

## Choosing the right adapter

| Goal | Adapter |
|---|---|
| Transform each element | `.map(f)` |
| Keep matching elements | `.filter(pred)` |
| Transform + flatten | `.flat_map(f)` |
| Accumulate to one value | `.fold(init, f)` or `.reduce(f)` |
| Short-circuit search | `.find(pred)`, `.any(pred)`, `.all(pred)` |
| Collect into `Vec` | `.collect::<Vec<_>>()` |
| Collect into `HashMap` | `.collect::<HashMap<_, _>>()` |
| Count elements | `.count()` |
| Sum / product | `.sum::<T>()`, `.product::<T>()` |
| Pair with index | `.enumerate()` |
| Pair two iterators | `.zip(other)` |
| Skip / take | `.skip(n)`, `.take(n)`, `.skip_while(pred)`, `.take_while(pred)` |
| Flatten nested | `.flatten()` |
| Deduplicate consecutive | `.dedup()` (on sorted `Vec`) |

## Rules

- Prefer `iter()` (borrowing) over `into_iter()` (consuming) when you only read items
- Prefer `.iter().map(...).collect()` over a `for` loop that pushes into a `Vec`
- Use `.cloned()` / `.copied()` to convert `Iterator<Item = &T>` to `Iterator<Item = T>` cleanly
- Chain `.filter_map(f)` instead of `.filter(pred).map(f)` when both steps are needed
- Use `.peekable()` only when you genuinely need look-ahead — it adds a layer of wrapping
- Avoid calling `.collect()` and then immediately iterating again — stay lazy as long as possible

## Implementing `Iterator`

When implementing a custom iterator, implement `Iterator` and let the standard library blanket provide all adapters for free:

```rust
struct Counter { count: u32, max: u32 }

impl Iterator for Counter {
    type Item = u32;
    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        if self.count < self.max {
            self.count += 1;
            Some(self.count)
        } else {
            None
        }
    }
}
```

- Also implement `size_hint` when the length is known — it lets `collect` pre-allocate
- Implement `ExactSizeIterator` when you know the exact remaining count
- Implement `DoubleEndedIterator` when bidirectional traversal makes sense

## Common patterns

```rust
// Partition into two Vecs
let (evens, odds): (Vec<_>, Vec<_>) = numbers.iter().partition(|&&x| x % 2 == 0);

// Flatten Option results
let values: Vec<u32> = strings.iter()
    .filter_map(|s| s.parse::<u32>().ok())
    .collect();

// Build a HashMap from an iterator
let map: HashMap<&str, usize> = words.iter()
    .enumerate()
    .map(|(i, w)| (*w, i))
    .collect();

// Chain two iterators without allocating
let all = first.iter().chain(second.iter());
```

## Anti-patterns

```rust
// BAD — collect just to iterate again
let v: Vec<_> = iter.map(f).collect();
for x in v { ... }
// GOOD — stay lazy
for x in iter.map(f) { ... }

// BAD — index loop on a Vec when iterating in order
for i in 0..v.len() { process(v[i]); }
// GOOD
for item in &v { process(item); }
```
